    "summary": "A ban on digging household waste pits in Mogadishu has left hundreds of casual laborers without income. The Banadir Regional Administration hired private companies for waste collection, citing sanitation and safety improvements.",
    "content": "A new policy by the Banadir Regional Administration has disrupted the livelihoods of hundreds of informal workers in Mogadishu. The administration banned the practice of digging shallow pits outside homes for household waste disposal, a common method used by residents lacking formal waste management services. Instead, it has contracted private companies to collect garbage from neighborhoods up to three times per month, aiming to improve public sanitation and reduce safety risks, particularly for children and the elderly who might fall into uncovered pits.\n\nOne affected worker is Ibrahim Mohamed Fanay, 43, who previously earned between $5 and $10 per day digging waste pits. He is among many casual laborers who now face unemployment as the demand for their services has vanished. These workers, often from low-income and displaced communities, rely on such informal jobs to support their families in Mogadishu's fragile economy.\n\nThe policy shift highlights a broader tension between urban development and the protection of vulnerable workers. While the administration’s goal of cleaner, safer streets is widely supported, the sudden implementation has left hundreds without alternative income sources. The lack of a transition plan or support for displaced laborers raises concerns about economic exclusion.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, this story underscores the challenges of rapid urbanization in Mogadishu. Many diaspora members send remittances to relatives in the city, and the loss of informal jobs could increase dependency on foreign support. It also reflects the need for inclusive urban policies that consider the impact on marginalized groups.\n\nAs Mogadishu modernizes its infrastructure, balancing public health improvements with economic inclusion remains a critical challenge. Without social safety nets, the poorest residents risk being left behind in the capital's transformation.\n\nRead the original report from Radio Ergo here: https://radioergo.org/en/2026/07/mogadishu-city-upgrade-leaves-poor-and-displaced-workers-behind/",
